Posted @withrepost • @buynsellazhomes Safety- 

This one gets me fired up. It’s something not talked about enough in the real estate community. Yet time and time again agents find themselves victim to attacks or worse lose their life. 

The general population may not associate risk with the job title of REALTOR ® but that’s just not the case. We often work with clients that we meet via phone call or internet. We also sit in vacant homes for open-houses. Along with holding access to keys to majority of homes on the market. Some of which may still be occupied with valuables. 

I’m going to be honest. I haven’t always been comfortable with the idea of conceal carry. Mostly just an unrealistic anxiety that I was going to shoot myself 🙃 #overthinker. My husband and #armyveteran had helped in making me more comfortable with a #pewpew and at the end of the day is my first line of defense.

If at all possible i schedule meeting new clients when my husband is available to attend. I also do not host open houses alone. I either bring the hubs, another agent like my bff @mollymovesaz or a lending partner like @breckisaloaner . 

If you are doing work along make sure someone knows who you are meeting, where you are going. Have a check in time. There’s also some apps available to call emergency contacts from your phone if you do not turn the safety alert off. 

Be diligent in your safety. If you are comfortable carrying then do that, if you aren’t have a plan.

I recently had the pleasure of taking a class called Progressive Folding Knife taught by Chris Fry of @mdts_training 😁🙌

Two of the things that really stood out to me in the class are the importance of a knife truly fitting our hand (a challenging task for those of us with small hands ✋) and the distinct advantage of being able to access and deploy a defensive knife with either hand.  Both of these knives fit my hand perfectly 😘🤌 Either one can be carried on my waistband toward the front of my body and can be accessed with either hand (been working on that lefty folding knife deployment 😅) or if you wanna be knifey-extra you can just carry both! 💃🏻💃🏻

🔪 Another POINT worth mentioning (haha point….get it?? 😂) is thinking about pocket placement.  I’ve always carried my knife in my pocket based on where it would fit comfortably. If you’re pocket-challenged like I am, you probably do the same thing.  If you put your knife in the wrong place, it can get pushed up and out of the pocket or limit your mobility.  This is worth testing out, though, because placing it “where it fits” may give you a sloppy (or inaccessible) draw in an emergency.  Can you get it quickly? Can you keep it securely in your hand as you open it? What about if you’re being jostled or distracted?  Self defense isn’t pretty.  It may not be from a standing position.  Challenge your preconceptions and see if your gear can meet your expectations! 💪

THE WINNING FORMULA -> A SOLID FOUNDATION + AN EYECATCHING DISTRACTION = SUCCESSFUL CONCEALED CARRY
 
You’re not gonna believe how simple this can be.

With any outfit, it’s important to match the support of the foundation (whether a bra or waistband or belt) to the weight of the gun. If the foundation doesn’t support the weight of the gun properly, it will sag down and move throughout the day - not only will it drive you completely batty, but the constant adjusting will draw unwanted attention. A few minor adjustments are totally understandable, but the basic idea of “set it and forget it” applies perfectly here. 
 
The second part of the formula is the distraction. This is the fun part! Printed clothing or fabric that drapes and flows make a world of difference when it comes to where the eye is drawn.  Beautiful fashion accessories in the form of layers (whether its a blazer, a kimono, a scarf, or even a bold necklace) direct the viewer’s eye, and girl, you can wield that power like a weapon!

A little behind-the-scenes action from our last photo shoot 📸 You better believe the Flashbang girls are always having fun! 💃🏻💃🏻 Be sure to tag your favorite 2A-related accounts below!  No gatekeeping here…let’s help each other GROW 🔫🔫🔫

1️⃣ Got involved with a women’s shooting group.  @agagclub is the one I chose! There are chapters all over the country, so there’s a good possibility you’ll find one near you.  If not, there are other great options available to you…shoot us a DM and we can point you in the right direction! The benefits of joining a group like this are: the community -you get to spend time around like-minded women. The education -no matter what your area of interest, classes are available to help you refine your skills. Access to a LOT of different guns….which leads me to ⤵️

2️⃣Tried LOTS of different guns.  You may think you know what firearm will suit you best, or you may have been TOLD by someone else which gun to carry.  This will all fly out the window when you get a little hands-on time with a variety of firearms.  We refer to this as a “wedding dress moment” 👰‍♀️ All wedding dresses are pretty…lacy…white…whatever…. but then you find THE ONE that makes you feel like a princess and 😍😍😍 Same thing happens with guns!  Definitely try before you buy.

3️⃣ Practice the different aspects of carry OFF the range.  It’s important to practice with your gun, but you don’t have to be on a range every time you do it.  Dryfire is a FANTASTIC way to practice your shooting skills without needing to get all geared up, or spend money on range fees and ammo.  You need to make sure you do this safely, though, and there are a TON of resources online to explain the technique.  Drawing your firearm from your holster is another aspect of off-range practice.
